"Written evidence submitted by Young Legal Aid Lawyers (YLAL) (LAI 0033)&#xa0;ABOUT US&#xa0;&#xa0;\nINTRODUCTION&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n(1)&#xa0;&#xa0; \nTHE IMPACT ON JUNIOR LAWYERS AND ACCESS TO JUSTICE&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nAll of the proposals assume that the quality of advice provided to legal aid clients remains unchanged. In the case of solicitors in public family and immigration law, we believe more junior professionals are able to provide a sufficiently high quality ser\nvice to enable individuals to be \nadequately represented should more senior solicitors take on less of this type of work. \n&#xa0;\nWe find this assumption concerning.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n(2) MEMBERâ€™S CASE STUDIES&#xa0;\nThe residence test:&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nPrison law:&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nJudicial review:&#xa0;Borderline cases&#xa0;\n(3) THE CONSTITUTIONAL IMPORTANCE OF ACCESS TO JUSTICE&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSeptember 2013\n4\n&#xa0;\n There is to be a 10% cut to fees paid to family solicitors in public law cases, a 50% cut to barristers fees in civil proceedings and the 35% uplift which may be payable in immigration cases in the Upper Tribunal is to be removed.\n Undertaken for a repor\nt on social mobility in the legal profession to be published in October 2013.\n \nhttps://consult.justice.gov\n.uk/digital-communications/transforming-legal-aid-next-steps/supporting_documents/latcivilfeesresponseia.pdf\n \n"